    {'id':'y3-t1-w1-l1','year':'Y3','term':'T1',     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'words ending in -le/-el/-al/-il',     'explanation':'The -le ending is the most common way to spell the /ul/ sound at the end of a word (table, simple, bottle). The -el ending usually comes after the letters m, n, r, s, v or w (tunnel, camel, squirrel). The -al ending is most often found in adjectives (magical, natural, brutal). The -il ending is rare and just has to be learned (pencil, nostril, pupil).',     'hlWords':['table', 'pencil', 'animal', 'tunnel', 'squirrel', 'uncle', 'stable', 'beetle', 'paddle', 'jingle']},
    {'id':'y3-t1-w1-l2','year':'Y3','term':'T1',     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'-el ending is often preceded by the letters m, n, r, s, v or w',     'explanation':'The -le ending is the most common way to spell the /ul/ sound at the end of a word. The -el ending usually comes after the letters m, n, r, s, v or w (tunnel, camel, squirrel, swivel). The -al ending is most common in adjectives (magical, natural). The -il ending is rare and just has to be learned (pencil, nostril, pupil).',     'hlWords':['tunnel', 'camel', 'squirrel', 'vessel', 'shovel', 'novel', 'national', 'magical', 'royal', 'humble']},
    {'id':'y3-t1-w1-l3','year':'Y3','term':'T1',     'week':1,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 3',     'focus':'-el ending is often preceded by the letters m, n, r, s, v or w',     'explanation':'The -le ending is the most common way to spell the /ul/ sound at the end of a word. The -el ending usually comes after the letters m, n, r, s, v or w (tunnel, camel, squirrel, swivel). The -al ending is most common in adjectives (magical, natural). The -il ending is rare and just has to be learned (pencil, nostril, pupil).',     'hlWords':['tunnel', 'squirrel', 'camel', 'channel', 'gravel', 'handle', 'musical', 'paddle', 'novel', 'vessel']},
    {'id':'y3-t1-w2-l1','year':'Y3','term':'T1',     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 4',     'focus':'applying -es to words ending in a',     'explanation':'For words ending in a consonant + y, change the y to i before adding -es (lady → ladies, baby → babies). For words ending in s, sh, ch or x, add -es rather than just -s (buses, churches, boxes). Simply adding an s would make these words difficult or impossible to say.',     'hlWords':['countries', 'libraries', 'cities', 'parties', 'pennies', 'enemies', 'valleys', 'chimneys', 'destroys', 'stories']},
    {'id':'y3-t1-w2-l2','year':'Y3','term':'T1',     'week':2,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 5',     'focus':'when a word ends in a consonant + y, we replace the y with i before…',     'explanation':'When a word ends in a consonant followed by y, change the y to i before adding most suffixes (carry → carried, happy → happiness, ugly → ugliest). The exception: if the suffix starts with i, keep the y (carry → carrying, copy → copying).',     'hlWords':['armies', 'jellies', 'mysteries', 'cities', 'fairies', 'parties', 'monkeys', 'obeys', 'surveys', 'babies']},
    {'id':'y3-t1-w2-l3','year':'Y3','term':'T1',     'week':2,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 6',     'focus':'when a word ends in a consonant + y, we replace the y with i before…',     'explanation':'When a word ends in a consonant followed by y, change the y to i before adding most suffixes (carry → carried, happy → happiness, ugly → ugliest). The exception: if the suffix starts with i, keep the y (carry → carrying, copy → copying).',     'hlWords':['families', 'diaries', 'hobbies', 'enemies', 'countries', 'delays', 'cowboys', 'stories', 'parties', 'babies']},
    {'id':'y3-t1-w3-l1','year':'Y3','term':'T1',     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 7',     'focus':'applying vowel suffixes to words',     'explanation':'When adding a vowel suffix (-ing, -ed, -er, -est), check the final letters of the root word carefully. If the word ends in a silent e, remove it first (hope → hoping). If a stressed syllable ends in a single short vowel + single consonant, double it (run → running). Otherwise, just add the suffix.',     'hlWords':['making', 'hoping', 'carrying', 'running', 'swimming', 'burying', 'terrifying', 'hopped', 'smiling', 'funniest']},
    {'id':'y3-t1-w3-l2','year':'Y3','term':'T1',     'week':3,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 8',     'focus':'when a word ends in a consonant + y, we change the y to i before…',     'explanation':'When a word ends in a consonant followed by y, change the y to i before adding most suffixes (carry → carried, happy → happiness, ugly → ugliest). The exception: if the suffix starts with i, keep the y (carry → carrying, copy → copying).',     'hlWords':['carried', 'babies', 'happier', 'ugliest', 'replied', 'lucky', 'noisy', 'grumpy', 'happiness', 'funnier']},
    {'id':'y3-t1-w3-l3','year':'Y3','term':'T1',     'week':3,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 9',     'focus':'when a word ends in a consonant + e, we remove the e before adding…',     'explanation':'When we add a vowel suffix to a word ending in a silent e, we remove the e first (make → making, hope → hoped, shine → shining). The e is no longer needed because the vowel suffix itself keeps the previous vowel long.',     'hlWords':['making', 'coming', 'racing', 'smiling', 'hoped', 'shiny', 'closer', 'breezy', 'escaped', 'latest']},
    {'id':'y3-t1-w4-l1','year':'Y3','term':'T1',     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 10',     'focus':'doubling consonants when adding',     'explanation':'When adding a vowel suffix to a word, double the final consonant only if the stressed syllable ends in a single short vowel + single consonant (begin → beginning, prefer → preferred). If the stress falls on an earlier syllable, just add the suffix (garden → gardening, listen → listened).',     'hlWords':['running', 'swimming', 'stopped', 'tapping', 'hottest', 'snapping', 'flattest', 'thinnest', 'planned', 'flipper']},
    {'id':'y3-t1-w4-l2','year':'Y3','term':'T1',     'week':4,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 11',     'focus':'when we apply a vowel suffix to a one-syllable root word ending in…',     'explanation':'When a one-syllable word ends in a single short vowel and a single consonant, double the consonant before adding a vowel suffix (run → running, hop → hopping). This preserves the short vowel sound.',     'hlWords':['running', 'swimming', 'stopped', 'hotter', 'saddest', 'funny', 'flipped', 'flattest', 'hitting', 'fatter']},
