    {'id':'y3-t1-w5-l3','year':'Y3','term':'T1',     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 15',     'focus':'there is more than one word ending in s',     'explanation':'Some words end in s because they are plurals (cats, dogs). Others are singular nouns that happen to end in s (bus, class, princess). To form the plural of words ending in s, ss, sh, ch or x, add -es rather than just -s (buses, classes, churches).',     'hlWords':['buses', 'classes', 'churches', 'boxes', 'dishes', 'brushes', 'foxes', 'benches', 'dresses', 'wishes']},
    {'id':'y3-t2-w1-l1','year':'Y3','term':'T2',     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Sequence 2','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'for most root words, the suffix -ly is simply added',     'explanation':'The suffix -ly turns an adjective into an adverb (kind → kindly, quick → quickly). For most root words, -ly is simply added directly. If the root ends in -le, replace the -le with -ly (simple → simply, gentle → gently). If it ends in -y, change the y to i (happy → happily). If it ends in -ic, add -ally (frantic → frantically).',     'hlWords':['kindly', 'quickly', 'friendly', 'certainly', 'slowly', 'completely', 'monthly', 'cowardly', 'softly', 'clearly']},
