    {'id':'y3-t2-w4-l1','year':'Y3','term':'T2',     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Lesson 1','lesson':'',     'focus':'doubling consonants when adding vowel suffixes',     'explanation':'When we add a vowel suffix (such as -ing, -ed or -er) to a word, we sometimes need to double the final consonant. This happens when a one-syllable word ends in a single short vowel followed by a single consonant (run → running, hop → hopped). Doubling keeps the vowel sound short.',     'hlWords':['running', 'sitting', 'hitting', 'hopping', 'cutting', 'stopped', 'fatter', 'hottest', 'swimming', 'planned']},
    {'id':'y3-t2-w4-l2','year':'Y3','term':'T2',     'week':4,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Lesson 2','lesson':'',     'focus':'when the first syllable of a word is stressed, we simply add the…',     'explanation':'When adding a vowel suffix to a word of more than one syllable, first find where the stress falls. If the first syllable is stressed, simply add the suffix without doubling (enter → entering, listen → listened, open → opening). The final consonant is not doubled because the syllable is not stressed.',     'hlWords':['opening', 'listened', 'happening', 'entered', 'offering', 'limited', 'gardening', 'covering', 'gathering', 'ordering']},
    {'id':'y3-t2-w4-l3','year':'Y3','term':'T2',     'week':4,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Lesson 3','lesson':'',     'focus':'when the second syllable of a word is stressed, we double the…',     'explanation':'When the stress falls on the final syllable of a word ending in a single vowel and consonant, double the consonant before adding a vowel suffix (begin → beginning, prefer → preferred, control → controlled). Doubling is needed because the final syllable is stressed.',     'hlWords':['beginning', 'preferred', 'forgetting', 'admitted', 'controlled', 'deterring', 'committed', 'regretting', 'omitting', 'permitted']},
    {'id':'y3-t2-w5-l1','year':'Y3','term':'T2',     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Lesson 4','lesson':'',     'focus':'when the second syllable of a word is stressed, we double the…',     'explanation':'Whether to double the final consonant depends on where the stress falls. If the stress is on the last syllable, double it (commit → committed, regret → regretting). If the stress is on an earlier syllable, just add the suffix (open → opened, offer → offering). Listening to the word carefully is the key.',     'hlWords':['committed', 'regretting', 'preferring', 'opened', 'offering', 'controller', 'beginning', 'happening', 'limiting', 'omitting']},
    {'id':'y3-t2-w5-l2','year':'Y3','term':'T2',     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Lesson 5','lesson':'',     'focus':'when the second syllable of a word is stressed, we double the…',     'explanation':'This lesson practises the stress-and-doubling rule across a mixed set of words. When the final syllable is stressed, double the final consonant before a vowel suffix (refer → referred, propel → propelling). When the stress falls on an earlier syllable, just add the suffix (limit → limiting, follow → follower).',     'hlWords':['referred', 'forgotten', 'propelling', 'limiting', 'follower', 'inferred', 'beginning', 'happening', 'committed', 'entering']},
    {'id':'y3-t2-w5-l3','year':'Y3','term':'T2',     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Lesson 6','lesson':'',     'focus':'',     'explanation':'This lesson draws together different rules for adding suffixes. Some words simply add the suffix (enjoyed, entering), some double the final consonant because the last syllable is stressed (beginning, recurring), and others follow different patterns. Always check where the stress falls before deciding whether to double.',     'hlWords':['beginning', 'happening', 'entering', 'committing', 'enjoyed', 'controlling', 'recurring', 'obeying', 'unlocking', 'attacked']},
    {'id':'y3-t3-w1-l1','year':'Y3','term':'T3',     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Sequence 3','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'words all end with the suffix -ous',     'explanation':"The suffix -ous means 'full of' or 'having the quality of'. For most root words, -ous is simply added (danger → dangerous, joy → joyous). If the root ends in e, remove it (adventure → adventurous, fame → famous). If the root ends in ge, keep the e so the g stays soft (courage → courageous).",     'hlWords':['dangerous', 'famous', 'courageous', 'nervous', 'joyous', 'thunderous', 'venomous', 'perilous', 'ruinous', 'outrageous']},
