    {'id':'y6-t5-w1-l1','year':'Y6','term':'T5',     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Year 6 Revision - Lesson 1','lesson':'',     'focus':'',     'explanation':'Many common words contain letters that are not spoken (written, glisten, knuckle, thistle, design, climb). Silent letters are often found in words borrowed from other languages. Learning to spot the silent letter in each word is the most reliable strategy.',     'hlWords':['climb', 'guard', 'guitar', 'written', 'design', 'knowledge', 'knight', 'campaign', 'autumn', 'column']},
    {'id':'y6-t5-w1-l2','year':'Y6','term':'T5',     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Year 6 Revision - Lesson 2','lesson':'',     'focus':'',     'explanation':"In words borrowed from Greek, ch makes the /k/ sound (monarch, anchor, character, stomach). In words from French, ch makes the /sh/ sound (brochure, chalet). The letters sc can make the /s/ sound before e or i (scenery, science, descend). Knowing a word's origin can help with these tricky spellings.",     'hlWords':['character', 'stomach', 'monarch', 'anchor', 'descend', 'scenery', 'brochure', 'fascinate', 'scientist', 'scheme']},
